    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-11-07T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-11-07T01:00:00-05:00" n="191"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/11–749: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Australia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jarman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canberra</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-11-07T16:00:00+10:00"
                            >November 7, 1949—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 7—8:12 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>237. Today’s press carries story Australia is preparing recognize Communist
                    regime China in near future. With these and Depintel November 2, 1 a. m.,<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d191fn3">Not printed.</note> in mind, Foster<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d191fn4">Andrew B. Foster, Counselor of Embassy in Australia.</note>
                    asked Burton<note n="5" xml:id="d191fn5">John W. Burton, Secretary of the
                        Australian Department of External Affairs.</note> whether there had been any
                    change in Australian position. Burton said Australia still stood by position
                    outlined Embtel 224, October 24, and had so informed UK in reply latter’s recent
                    approach. Added that in any <pb facs="0190" n="180" xml:id="pg_180"/> case
                    Government would not consider recognition before the federal elections on
                    December 10 (the Government is being criticized by opposition for alleged
                    failure deal vigorously with Communists in Australia). Burton dismissed press
                    stories as lies.</p>
                <p>Burton said his information was New Zealand strongly opposed to recognition while
                    India would grant it ahead of everybody else.</p>
                <p>Sent Department. Department pass London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jarman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
